In Godot (Real-time, in-engine)
WorldEnvironment + Environment Resource is your main hub for post-processing. Key settings for a stylized look:

Tonemapping — Try the "Filmic" or "ACES" tonemapper for punchy, cinematic contrast, or keep it flat and push color manually.
Glow/Bloom — A soft, low-intensity bloom can make sunlight filtering through trees feel magical. Godot's glow has a "bicubic upscale" option that looks much softer.
Screen-Space Ambient Occlusion (SSAO) — Adds depth to foliage and ground contact shadows without heavy rendering cost.
Depth of Field — Blur distant elements or foreground grass to create a painterly, shallow-focus feel.
Color Correction via LUT — You can load a custom color lookup table (LUT) to apply a whole "mood" in one step — great for a warm golden hour Central Park vibe or a cool overcast morning.
Fog — Godot's volumetric or distance fog can soften the horizon and give the park a hazy, atmospheric depth.

Stylized tip: Combine a slightly desaturated base with boosted glow and a warm LUT — this is a common trick for that "storybook outdoors" aesthetic.

In Blender (Pre-render / Offline)
If you're rendering cinematic shots or cutscenes out of Blender before bringing them into Godot:

Compositor nodes — This is the powerhouse. You can chain Glare, Color Balance, Lens Distortion, Vignette, and more non-destructively.
Glare node — Specifically the "Bloom" or "Streaks" type for stylized sun rays through the Central Park canopy.
Color Balance (ASC-CDL) — Lift/Gamma/Gain gives you precise filmic color control.
Halftone or painterly shaders — If you want something more illustrative, you can use Blender's Geometry Nodes or shader tricks to push toward a watercolor or graphic novel look.


Stylistic Directions Worth Considering
Given it's Central Park, a few aesthetic approaches that work really well:

Golden hour warmth — Warm LUT, soft bloom, slight vignette
Impressionistic/painterly — Cel shading in Godot + toon outline shader + Blender compositor stylization
Moody overcast — Desaturated palette, heavy SSAO, subtle fog, cooler color grade
Storybook illustration — Flat lighting, strong outlines, bold saturated colors


