Weather/Effect Overlays — Key Techniques
Rain

GPUParticles3D with downward velocity, slight random spread
Screen-space rain drop texture via a CanvasLayer shader
Boost fog density slightly, desaturate color grade
Wet ground: increase surface roughness/reflectivity on materials

Snow

GPUParticles3D with slow drift + sine wave horizontal movement
Larger, softer particles than rain
Brighten ambient slightly (snow reflects light)
Optional accumulation on geometry via a secondary albedo blend shader

Fog

Godot's volumetric fog in WorldEnvironment — density ~0.08, height falloff
Reduce sun energy by ~40%
Great combined with Dawn or Dusk for a moody Central Park morning

Lens Distortion + Huge FOV

Set Camera3D.fov to 110–140° (play with it — 120° is a sweet spot for surreal but navigable)
Apply a barrel distortion shader on a CanvasLayer fullscreen quad:

glsl// Barrel distortion fragment shader
uniform float strength = 0.3;
void fragment() {
    vec2 uv = SCREEN_UV - 0.5;
    float dist = dot(uv, uv);
    uv *= 1.0 + strength * dist;
    COLOR = texture(SCREEN_TEXTURE, uv + 0.5);
}

Add chromatic aberration (RGB channel offset) for extra weirdness

Clear

No particles, no distortion, standard fog settings off


Combinability
Since --time and --weather are independent, you get combos like night + snow (blue moonlit snowfall), dawn + fog (misty park morning), or noon + lens (blazing sun with a fisheye feel) totally for free. You may want to add a few override tweaks — e.g. fog should reduce sun energy regardless of time preset — which you can handle with a post-apply pass in SimulationManager.
